{{globalize/US|date=June 2015}}

A '''protest permit''' or '''parade permit''' is permission granted by a governmental agency for a demonstration to be held in a particular venue at a particular time. Failing to obtain a permit may lead to charges of parading without a permit. The requirement of a permit is sometimes denounced as an infringement of [[free speech]],<ref>{{citation|title=The Interaction of State Repression, Protest Form and Protest Sponsor Strength During the Transition from Communism in Minsk, Belarus, 1990-1995|publisher=Mobilization: An International Quarterly|volume=6|number=2|date=Fall 2001|pages=129–150}}</ref> as permits are denied on spurious grounds or protestors are corralled into [[free speech zone]]s. Permits are sometimes denied on grounds that the protest will create a security risk.<ref>{{citation|title=Permitting protest: parsing the fine geography of dissent in America|author=D Mitchell, LA Staeheli|publisher=International Journal of Urban|date=2005}}</ref> There seems to be evidence that the available venues for protests are shrinking in number; that citizens have experienced increasing difficulty in gaining unrestricted access to them; and that such venues are no longer where most people typically congregate in large numbers.<ref>{{citation|title=Places of Protest: The Public Forum in Principle and Practice|publisher=Mobilization: An International Quarterly|volume=11|number=2|date=June 2006|pages=229–247}}</ref> In [[Washington, DC]], the [[National Park Service Police]], [[U.S. Capitol Police]], and [[Metropolitan Police of the District of Columbia]] have an elaborate permitting system.<ref>{{citation|title=Policing protest: the control of mass demonstrations in Western democracies|author=Donatella Della Porta, Herbert Reiter}}</ref> Many famous people such as [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] have been arrested for protesting without a permit.

