{{featured article}} {{Use Canadian English|date=March 2015}} {{Italic title}} [[File:L-hyde-southern-cross-image-4.jpg|thumb|upright=2|A nuclear test obliterates a Pacific island]] <!-- No infobox, please --> '''''Southern Cross''''' is the sole [[wordless novel]] by Canadian artist [[Laurence Hyde (artist)|Laurence Hyde]] (1914–1987).{{sfn|Beronä|2008|p=213}} Published in [[1951 in literature|1951]], its 118 [[wood engraving|wood-engraved]] images narrate the impact of [[nuclear weapons testing|atomic testing]] on Pacific islanders. Hyde made the book to express his anger at the US military's [[Operation Crossroads|nuclear tests in the Bikini Atoll]].
The wordless novel genre had flourished primarily during the 1920s and 1930s, but by the 1940s even the most prolific practitioners had abandoned it. Hyde was familiar with some such works by [[Lynd Ward]], [[Otto Nückel]], and the form's pioneer [[Frans Masereel]]. The high-contrast artwork of ''Southern Cross'' features dynamic curving lines uncommon in wood engraving and combines abstract imagery with realistic detail. It has gained appreciation in comics circles as a precursor to the [[Canadian comics|Canadian graphic novel]], though it had no direct influence.
__TOC__
==Synopsis==
The story tells of the American military evacuating villagers from a Pacific island before testing nuclear weapons. A drunken soldier attempts to rape a fisherman's wife during the evacuation, and the fisherman kills him. To avoid capture, the couple run to the forests with their child and hide. The child witnesses the death of the parents and destruction of their environment from the ensuing atomic tests.{{sfn|Beronä|2008|pp=214–215}}
==Background==
[[File:Laurence Eveyln Hyde (1945).jpg|thumb|alt=Black-and-white photograph of a man in glasses resting his head on his hand and smiling at the camera|Laurence Hyde in 1945]]
Born in [[Kingston upon Thames]]{{sfn|Hyde|Beronä|2007}} in England in 1914, Laurence Hyde moved with his family to Canada in 1926. They settled in Toronto in 1928, where Hyde studied art{{sfn|Walker|2007|p=31}} at [[Central Technical School]].{{sfn|Hyde|Beronä|2007}} His strongest artistic influences included the painter [[Paul Nash (artist)|Paul Nash]] and the printmakers [[Eric Gill]], [[Rockwell Kent]], and [[Lynd Ward]]; he corresponded with Kent and Ward.{{sfn|Beronä|2008|p=213}}
From the 1930s Hyde did commercial pen-and-ink and [[scratchboard]] illustrations, ran a business providing advertising illustrations, and made [[wood engraving]]s and [[linocut]]s for books. He attempted but gave up on two series of prints, titled ''Discovery'' and ''Macbeth''. Hyde worked in [[Ottawa]] for the [[National Film Board of Canada]] from 1942 until his 1972 retirement.{{sfn|Beronä|2008|p=213}}
The [[wordless novel]] had been popular in the 1920s and 1930s, but had become rare by the 1940s. Such books tended to be melodramatic works about social injustice.{{sfn|Rogers|2008b}} Hyde was familiar with some of Ward's books and the German [[Otto Nückel]]'s ''[[Destiny (wordless novel)|Destiny]]'' (1926). The only work he knew of the Flemish artist [[Frans Masereel]], the form's first and most prolific practitioner, was ''[[Passionate Journey]]'' (1919), which he had read in a 1949 American edition.{{sfn|Cohen|1977|p=195}} Like his forebears in the genre, Hyde had a [[left-wing politics|left-wing]] agenda that he expressed in his art.{{sfn|Bell|2006|p=103}} When ''Southern Cross'' appeared, the genre had been out of the public eye for so long that Hyde included a historical essay to orient the reader.{{sfn|A.V. Club staff|2007}} Hyde had asked Ward to proofread this history, but the book was published without Ward's corrections—errors remained, such as Masereel's forename given as "Hans", and a listing of only four of Ward's six wordless novels.{{sfn|Hyde|Beronä|2007}}
==Creation and publication==
{{Quote |text = Words are capable of expressing very complicated and very subtle notions&nbsp;... But for directness and universal interpretation, pictures, under certain conditions, are unrivalled. It really depends on what you want to say.{{sfn|Beauman|2007}} |sign = [[Laurence Hyde (artist)|Laurence Hyde]] |source = Afterword to ''Southern Cross''}}
[[File:Operation Crossroads Baker Edit.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Photograph of a mushroom cloud explosion in a tropical setting|The [[Operation Crossroads|nuclear tests in the Bikini Atoll]] in 1946 motivated Hyde to make the book.]]
Hyde made ''Southern Cross'' to express his anger at American [[Operation Crossroads|nuclear tests in the Bikini Atoll]] in 1946 following the [[Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|atomic bombings in Japan]].{{sfn|Beronä|2008|p=214}} He worked on it from 1948 to 1951.{{sfn|Beronä|2008|p=214}} Each image is {{convert|4|x|3|in|cm}},{{sfn|Beronä|2008|p=215}} centred at the top third of the page and with broad margins.{{sfn|Hinton|2008}} The one exception is of the bomb detonating, a {{convert|7|x|6|in|cm|abbr=on}} full-page image that [[bleed (printing)|bleeds]] off the page.{{sfn|Beronä|2008|p=215}} Hyde carved dynamic curving lines uncommon in wood engraving. Blacks overwhelms the figures they surround, and abstract images contrast with realistic detail in the flora and fauna.{{sfn|Rogers|2008b}}
''Southern Cross'' was published in a limited edition by [[Ward Ritchie Press]] in 1951{{sfn|Beronä|2008|p=214}} on [[Washi|Japanese paper]]{{sfn|National Gallery of Canada staff}} with the images on the [[recto and verso|recto]] and the verso left blank. Rockwell Kent provided the introduction.{{sfn|Pantaleo|2008}} Hyde dedicated the book to the [[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|Red Cross Societies]] and the [[Quakers|Society of Friends]].{{sfnm|1a1=Cohen|1y=1977|1p=195|2a1=Beronä|2y=2008|2p=216}} He was not present at the book's pressing and thus was not able to correct some blocks that he had not carved deeply enough to produce satisfactory prints.{{sfn|Hyde|Beronä|2007}}
The book was republished twice in 2007: [[Drawn and Quarterly]] released a deluxe facsimile edition with additional essays by Hyde and an introduction by wordless novel historian David Beronä,{{sfn|Pantaleo|2008}} and [[George Walker (printmaker)|George Walker]] included ''Southern Cross'' in his anthology of wordless novels ''Graphic Witness''.{{sfn|Hinton|2008}}
==Reception and legacy==
[[File:Frans Masereel - 25 Images of a Man's Passion - final four plates.jpg|thumb|alt=Four high-contrast black-and-white images in sequence. In the first, a man, facing left with his right arm aloft, marches with a crowd towards a group of gun-wielding figures. In the second, uniformed figures are taking the man away amongst a crowd. In the third, the man is seen from behind at the bottom, with a group seated behind a bench in the distance near the top in an apparent courtroom. A crucifix hangs prominently above the bench, bathed in light in the darkened room. In the fourth, the man has his back to a wall, hands bound behind him, with another figure lying apparently dead at his feet. He faces right, apparently awaiting his execution by gunfire.|[[Frans Masereel]]'s ''[[Passionate Journey]]'' (1919) and other [[wordless novel]]s influenced Hyde.]]
{{Quote |text = Man&nbsp;... can tie himself up in words to the point of persuading himself that dropping atom bombs on people he's never seen is a kind of shrewd move in an exciting chess game. He needs something simpler, like pictures, to remind him of what dropping bombs on innocent people is really like.{{sfn|Frye|2002|p=314}} |sign = [[Northrop Frye]] |source = [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] review, 1952}}
In a talk with the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] in 1952, literary critic [[Northrop Frye]] praised Hyde's visual skills, but said, "There's no point in getting the book for your library unless you like the engravings themselves as separate works of art."{{sfn|Frye|2002|p=314}} He found the book a quick read in contrast to the time it took to make it, and called its "continuity" a weak point. He considered the visualization of the bomb's destruction of living things the strongest justification for the work.{{sfn|Frye|2002|p=314}}
Comics critic Sean Rogers praised the work, particularly the pacing and action sequences, but felt it had less impact than such earlier works as Masereel's ''[[Passionate Journey]]'' (1919) or Ward's ''[[Vertigo (wordless novel)|Vertigo]]'' (1937). Rogers found the anti-nuclear message less effective than that of later comics such as [[Keiji Nakazawa]]'s ''[[Barefoot Gen]]'' or [[Gary Panter]]'s ''[[Jimbo (comics)|Jimbo]]''.{{sfn|Rogers|2008b}} Comics scholar [[Roger Sabin]] found the book unconvincing, "a well-meaning but facile piece of [[agitprop|agit-prop]]".{{sfn|Sabin|2007}} Reviewer Erik Hinton praised the artwork while calling the story "the progeny of historical lip-service and the hot-button anxiety of the destructivity of modern warfare", and considered Ward and others of Hyde's predecessors more proficient at the medium.{{sfn|Hinton|2008}}
''Southern Cross'' has gained appreciation in comics circles as a precursor to the [[graphic novel]] in Canada, though it had no direct influence on [[Canadian comics]]—it was marketed to book connoisseurs, a world far removed from that of consumers of cheap entertainment that comics served in the 1950s.{{sfn|Bell|2006|p=103}} Copies of ''Southern Cross'' joined the collections of the [[National Gallery of Canada]]{{sfn|Spurgeon|2010}} in 1952{{sfn|National Gallery of Canada staff}} and the [[Burnaby Art Gallery]] in 1987.{{sfn|Spurgeon|2010}} The book received an {{not a typo|honorable}} mention for Best Book at the 2008 [[Doug Wright Award|Doug Wright Awards for Canadian Cartooning]], accepted by Hyde's son, Anthony.{{sfn|Rogers|2008a}}
